servings: 2
author: HelloFresh
course: main course
time required: 20 minutes
---

Bring a #medium pot{} of @water{} and @salt{} to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @onion{1}. Halve, core, and thinly slice @green bell pepper{1} into strips. Using the tip of a #spoon{}, remove and discard black gills from undersides of @portobello mushrooms{2}; trim any large stems if necessary. Thinly slice mushrooms into strips (if strips are too long, cut them in half crosswise).

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together @honey{4%tsp}, @miso sauce concentrate{1}, half the @soy sauce{2%tbsp}, half the @rice wine vinegar{5%tsp}, half the @szechuan paste{2%tbsp} (use more for more heat), and 1⁄4 cup water.

Rinse @shrimp{10%oz} under cold water. Pat shrimp dry with #paper towels{}; season with salt and @pepper{}. Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{4%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add shrimp in a single layer; cook, stirring occasionally, until cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #plate{}. Wipe out pan.

Heat a large drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add onion, bell pepper, and mushrooms; cook, stirring occasionally, until softened and lightly browned, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Stir in Szechuan sauce mixture; cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce has reduced and slightly thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

> Use pan used for shrimp here.

Once water is boiling, add @lo mein noodles{4.5%oz} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{5-7%minutes}. Drain.

While noodles cook, roughly chop @peanuts{1%oz}.

Add drained noodles to pan with veggies; toss until noodles are thoroughly coated in sauce. Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

> Add shrimp to pan along with noodles.

Divide lo mein between shallow #bowls{}. Top with peanuts and serve.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.